1
00:00:21,160 --> 00:00:23,720
Friends, let me introduce myself.

2
00:00:24,040 --> 00:00:26,200
Peltzer's the name.
Rand Peltzer.

3
00:00:26,760 --> 00:00:28,520
That's me there on the corner.

4
00:00:29,120 --> 00:00:30,440
I'm an inventor.

5
00:00:30,720 --> 00:00:32,680
And I have a story to tell.

6
00:00:33,040 --> 00:00:35,400
I know.
Who hasn 't got a story?

7
00:00:35,640 --> 00:00:38,360
Well, nobody's got a story
like this one.

8
00:00:38,560 --> 00:00:40,160
Nobody.

9
00:00:40,440 --> 00:00:42,800
It all started here in Chinatown.

10
00:00:43,200 --> 00:00:45,680
I was trying
to move a little merchandise...

11
00:00:45,920 --> 00:00:48,160
...maybe find a present
for my kid.

12
00:00:48,440 --> 00:00:50,440
I tried this one place.

13
00:00:54,920 --> 00:00:55,720
Wait a minute.

14
00:00:57,440 --> 00:00:58,560
What's down here?

15
00:00:58,760 --> 00:00:59,920
This is it.

16
00:01:00,200 --> 00:01:02,440
This is your grandfather's store?

17
00:01:03,440 --> 00:01:04,640
Come on.

18
00:01:06,160 --> 00:01:08,960
No wonder you gotta drag
people in off the street.

19
00:01:14,400 --> 00:01:16,520
Go ahead, mister.
Look around.

20
00:01:16,720 --> 00:01:18,760
See if there's something you like.

21
00:01:37,760 --> 00:01:38,840
Are these things real?

22
00:01:39,040 --> 00:01:41,560
I told you. Everything's real.

23
00:01:43,920 --> 00:01:46,160
You do have
interesting artifacts here...

24
00:01:46,400 --> 00:01:48,160
...but there's one thing
you don't have.

25
00:01:48,400 --> 00:01:49,480
And what's that?

26
00:01:49,880 --> 00:01:53,000
Let me show you.
I'm an inventor. I made this.

27
00:01:53,600 --> 00:01:56,640
The Bathroom Buddy.
The invention of the century.

28
00:01:56,880 --> 00:02:01,000
It eliminates the need to carry
heavy luggage when you travel.

29
00:02:01,320 --> 00:02:04,080
You got yourself
your shaving mirror...

30
00:02:04,280 --> 00:02:08,200
...your toothbrush, a toothpick.
You got toenail clippers...

31
00:02:09,160 --> 00:02:10,240
...a nail file...

32
00:02:10,560 --> 00:02:12,960
...and you got yourself
a dental mirror.

33
00:02:13,160 --> 00:02:15,240
This is gonna revolutionize traveling.

34
00:02:15,720 --> 00:02:18,200
Let's just say,
for the sake of argument...

35
00:02:18,440 --> 00:02:20,680
...that you're on a bus,
a plane or a train.

36
00:02:21,360 --> 00:02:23,920
You forgot to brush your teeth.

37
00:02:24,560 --> 00:02:27,880
You got yourself a bad case
of dragon breath.

38
00:02:29,440 --> 00:02:30,840
Bad breath.

39
00:02:31,040 --> 00:02:31,880
What do you do?

40
00:02:32,520 --> 00:02:35,040
No problem, friend.
All you do is...

41
00:02:35,280 --> 00:02:36,880
...you take your toothbrush out...

42
00:02:37,240 --> 00:02:38,760
...and you push this button.

43
00:02:40,200 --> 00:02:41,960
That's absolutely no problem.

44
00:02:42,640 --> 00:02:44,600
Cleans up easily.

45
00:02:44,840 --> 00:02:47,560
What I'd like to do, sir,
is give you my card.

46
00:02:47,840 --> 00:02:50,960
Rand Peltzer. "Fantastic Ideas
for a Fantastic World. "

47
00:02:51,160 --> 00:02:52,600
I make the illogical logical.

48
00:02:53,440 --> 00:02:55,080
I can get you these.

49
00:02:55,360 --> 00:02:57,560
I can get them by the dozen
if you'd like.

50
00:03:01,400 --> 00:03:02,760
What do you think?

51
00:03:04,600 --> 00:03:05,800
What do you think?

52
00:03:09,040 --> 00:03:10,600
Where's that coming from?

53
00:03:29,160 --> 00:03:29,960
What is that?

54
00:03:30,160 --> 00:03:31,320
Mogwai.

55
00:03:34,520 --> 00:03:35,560
What's he doing?

56
00:03:35,840 --> 00:03:36,960
Singing.

57
00:03:37,640 --> 00:03:39,760
He does that sometimes.

58
00:03:45,480 --> 00:03:47,920
I gotta have him.
He's incredible.

59
00:03:48,880 --> 00:03:50,120
Tell you what I'll do.

60
00:03:50,360 --> 00:03:52,240
I'll give you $ 100 for him.

61
00:03:53,520 --> 00:03:56,520
I've gotta have him. It's a present
for my son for Christmas.

62
00:03:56,720 --> 00:03:58,400
It's what I've been looking for.

63
00:03:58,600 --> 00:04:01,000
I've been everywhere.
I'll give you $200.

64
00:04:01,320 --> 00:04:02,680
That's $200!

65
00:04:03,040 --> 00:04:04,240
I'm sorry.

66
00:04:04,600 --> 00:04:07,360
Mogwai not for sale.

67
00:04:08,640 --> 00:04:10,800
You said everything here was for sale.

68
00:04:11,000 --> 00:04:11,960
Grandfather!

69
00:04:12,160 --> 00:04:15,760
With mogwai comes much responsibility.

70
00:04:15,960 --> 00:04:19,160
I cannot sell him at any price.

71
00:04:24,760 --> 00:04:27,440
Wait outside. I'll be right out.

72
00:04:27,640 --> 00:04:28,960
Just go.

73
00:04:38,440 --> 00:04:40,960
Okay, mister. Here it is.

74
00:04:42,040 --> 00:04:43,240
What about your grandfather?

75
00:04:43,440 --> 00:04:46,120
Forget what he said. He's crazy.
We need the money.

76
00:04:46,320 --> 00:04:47,760
Do you want it or not?

77
00:04:47,960 --> 00:04:49,160
I want it.

78
00:04:50,840 --> 00:04:53,400
There's three rules
you've gotta follow.

79
00:04:53,640 --> 00:04:54,960
What kind of rules?

80
00:04:55,240 --> 00:04:56,560
Keep him out of the light.

81
00:04:56,760 --> 00:04:59,560
He hates bright light,
especially sunlight.

82
00:04:59,760 --> 00:05:00,920
It'll kill him.

83
00:05:01,120 --> 00:05:04,560
And keep him away from water.
Don 't get him wet.

84
00:05:04,760 --> 00:05:08,400
But the most important rule,
the rule you can never forget...

85
00:05:08,600 --> 00:05:11,720
...no matter how much he cries
or how much he begs...

86
00:05:11,960 --> 00:05:15,640
...never, never feed him
after midnight. Got it?

87
00:05:15,840 --> 00:05:17,160
Sure. Whatever you say.

88
00:05:17,360 --> 00:05:20,040
Thanks.
And have a Merry Christmas.

89
00:05:27,560 --> 00:05:30,200
You're rolling with
Rockin ' Ricky Rialto...

90
00:05:30,440 --> 00:05:33,120
...the voice of Kingston Falls, U. S.A.!

91
00:06:05,240 --> 00:06:06,560
Alex... .

92
00:06:06,960 --> 00:06:08,600
Getting close to Christmas.

93
00:06:08,840 --> 00:06:11,040
You'll get stuck
with a lot of trees again.

94
00:06:11,280 --> 00:06:14,200
I thought I'd be seeing you
about this time.

95
00:06:14,400 --> 00:06:15,720
What the hell is this?

96
00:06:16,640 --> 00:06:18,280
What are you doing in there?

97
00:06:18,560 --> 00:06:20,000
Don't ask.

98
00:06:20,240 --> 00:06:22,400
Alex, I came to get my tree.

99
00:06:22,600 --> 00:06:25,320
Pete, take that tree
to Mr. Anderson's truck.

100
00:06:27,120 --> 00:06:28,400
What do you say, Alex?

101
00:06:28,640 --> 00:06:30,640
You can spare one
for the sheriff's station.

102
00:06:30,840 --> 00:06:33,280
I paid for mine, Frank.

103
00:07:19,440 --> 00:07:21,000
Billy, you need a jump?

104
00:07:21,400 --> 00:07:24,360
No, thanks, Mr. Futterman.
I'm late for work as it is.

105
00:07:24,600 --> 00:07:27,320
These goddamn foreign cars
always freeze up on you.

106
00:07:27,640 --> 00:07:30,600
You don't find American
machinery doing that.

107
00:07:30,880 --> 00:07:31,960
See that plow?

108
00:07:32,320 --> 00:07:34,640
Hasn't given me a day's trouble
in 15 years.

109
00:07:34,840 --> 00:07:36,480
You know why?
Kentucky Harvester.

110
00:07:36,760 --> 00:07:40,680
It ain't some foreign piece of crap.
That's a Kentucky Harvester.

111
00:07:41,160 --> 00:07:44,040
If I wanna keep my job,
I should be going now.

112
00:07:44,240 --> 00:07:45,920
How's your comic strip coming?

113
00:07:46,360 --> 00:07:50,040
I expect to see you in the funnies
with "Smilin' Jack," "Li'I Abner. "

114
00:07:50,240 --> 00:07:52,440
They don't run those comics anymore.

115
00:07:52,640 --> 00:07:53,840
They don't?

116
00:07:54,240 --> 00:07:55,760
Come on, Barn.

117
00:07:56,240 --> 00:07:58,360
Say hello to your wife, okay?

118
00:07:58,560 --> 00:07:59,960
So long, Billy.

119
00:08:03,920 --> 00:08:06,160
Goddamn foreign cars.

120
00:08:29,800 --> 00:08:30,600
Hey, doctor.

121
00:08:30,800 --> 00:08:32,160
Morning, Billy.

122
00:09:05,360 --> 00:09:07,760
Get in there and be quiet.

123
00:09:25,240 --> 00:09:27,760
- You just made it.
- Again.

124
00:09:28,320 --> 00:09:29,840
Will you sign this petition?

125
00:09:30,040 --> 00:09:31,840
Sure. What's it for?

126
00:09:32,040 --> 00:09:34,000
To declare Dorry's pub a landmark.

127
00:09:34,240 --> 00:09:36,560
Mrs. Deagle's trying to take
his lease away.

128
00:09:36,840 --> 00:09:37,760
His too?

129
00:09:37,960 --> 00:09:41,120
Yeah, she says it's a dive,
a public nuisance.

130
00:09:41,320 --> 00:09:43,240
That's where my dad
proposed to my mom.

131
00:09:43,440 --> 00:09:46,960
That's where everybody's dad
proposed to their mom. Cross your "T. "

132
00:09:51,080 --> 00:09:52,080
Thanks.

133
00:09:59,360 --> 00:10:00,800
Good morning, Mrs. Deagle.

134
00:10:01,000 --> 00:10:02,560
What's good about it?

135
00:10:05,800 --> 00:10:07,000
Klutz!

136
00:10:09,640 --> 00:10:11,240
Watch it, watch it!

137
00:10:11,720 --> 00:10:14,440
40, 60, 80... .

138
00:10:21,120 --> 00:10:23,480
200. Thank you.

139
00:10:23,920 --> 00:10:25,160
- Mrs. Deagle?
- What?

140
00:10:25,360 --> 00:10:28,200
I just wanted you to know
that Joe got another job.

141
00:10:28,440 --> 00:10:29,680
My husband, Joe Harris.

142
00:10:29,880 --> 00:10:31,560
And I've taken up some sewing.

143
00:10:31,800 --> 00:10:33,480
What are you trying to tell me?

144
00:10:34,000 --> 00:10:36,560
Neither of us will be paid
for two weeks.

145
00:10:36,760 --> 00:10:38,640
Couldn't you get Mr. Corben...

146
00:10:39,120 --> 00:10:40,920
...to give us a little more time?

147
00:10:41,120 --> 00:10:42,000
Mrs. Harris...

148
00:10:42,400 --> 00:10:44,600
...the bank and I have
the same purpose in life:

149
00:10:44,840 --> 00:10:46,640
To make money.

150
00:10:46,840 --> 00:10:48,440
Not to support a lot of...

151
00:10:48,640 --> 00:10:49,760
...deadbeats.

152
00:10:51,160 --> 00:10:53,560
Mrs. Deagle, it's Christmas!

153
00:10:57,160 --> 00:11:00,360
Now you know what to ask Santa for,
don't you?

154
00:11:02,520 --> 00:11:04,080
Mommy, I'm hungry.

155
00:11:04,440 --> 00:11:06,600
Yes, honey. So am I.

156
00:11:12,120 --> 00:11:14,880
This is what's left
of my imported Bavarian snowman.

157
00:11:15,120 --> 00:11:17,760
Your dog broke it this morning!

158
00:11:19,320 --> 00:11:20,560
I'm terribly sorry.

159
00:11:20,760 --> 00:11:22,240
Tell me how much I owe you...

160
00:11:22,440 --> 00:11:23,960
I don't want money.

161
00:11:26,720 --> 00:11:28,840
I want your dog.

162
00:11:31,760 --> 00:11:32,960
Barney?

163
00:11:33,640 --> 00:11:35,640
Give him to me.

164
00:11:35,840 --> 00:11:38,840
I'll take him to the kennel.
They'll put him to sleep.

165
00:11:39,040 --> 00:11:42,200
It'll be quick and painless,
compared to what I could do to him.

166
00:11:42,960 --> 00:11:44,280
What could you do?

167
00:11:47,240 --> 00:11:49,800
I'll catch the beast myself.

168
00:11:50,800 --> 00:11:52,800
Then he'll get what he deserves.

169
00:11:53,000 --> 00:11:55,440
A slow, painful death.

170
00:11:56,520 --> 00:12:00,000
Maybe I'll put him in my spin dryer
on high heat.

171
00:12:01,160 --> 00:12:02,280
That'd do it.

172
00:12:09,840 --> 00:12:11,720
Barney, will you get off of her?

173
00:12:11,920 --> 00:12:14,400
My dear lady, are you all right?

174
00:12:14,600 --> 00:12:17,720
I have a very weak heart.
I can't stand a shock like that!

175
00:12:17,920 --> 00:12:19,800
What is that dog doing in here?

176
00:12:20,040 --> 00:12:21,640
This is a bank, not a pet store.

177
00:12:21,840 --> 00:12:22,800
Very good, Gerald.

178
00:12:23,000 --> 00:12:24,240
He wouldn't hurt you.

179
00:12:24,440 --> 00:12:27,240
Excuses, excuses.
You're just like your father.

180
00:12:27,520 --> 00:12:31,560
I've listened to his excuses
for 10 years, the loser!

181
00:12:31,760 --> 00:12:34,560
As for you, you mangy cur...

182
00:12:34,920 --> 00:12:36,520
...I'll get you...

183
00:12:37,360 --> 00:12:39,160
...when you least expect it!

184
00:12:39,600 --> 00:12:40,960
Oh, my heart!

185
00:12:41,200 --> 00:12:43,960
I must apologize
for this most unusual... .

186
00:12:44,160 --> 00:12:45,760
You putz.

187
00:12:49,800 --> 00:12:51,600
The old bat never looked better.

188
00:12:52,000 --> 00:12:53,640
It's great. You're doing fine.

189
00:12:54,240 --> 00:12:55,400
Thanks.

190
00:12:55,720 --> 00:12:57,200
Hello, Gerald.

191
00:12:57,440 --> 00:13:00,360
If it isn't Captain Clip-on.

192
00:13:00,600 --> 00:13:03,840
Guess who almost applied
for unemployment today?

193
00:13:04,040 --> 00:13:06,240
- I give up.
- You.

194
00:13:06,440 --> 00:13:09,160
But Mr. Corben had second thoughts.

195
00:13:09,600 --> 00:13:11,920
He gets so sentimental
about the holidays.

196
00:13:12,120 --> 00:13:13,760
Imagine that.

197
00:13:14,440 --> 00:13:16,360
I would've fired you in a second.

198
00:13:17,000 --> 00:13:18,760
Merry Christmas to you too.

199
00:13:18,960 --> 00:13:20,760
Excuse me, Mr. Jones.

200
00:13:22,360 --> 00:13:23,960
Hey, Peltzer.

201
00:13:24,160 --> 00:13:27,160
Look, I'm a junior
vice president at 23.

202
00:13:27,360 --> 00:13:30,600
By the time I'm 25,
I'm gonna have Mr. Corben's job.

203
00:13:31,040 --> 00:13:33,080
By the time I'm 30,
I'll be a millionaire.

204
00:13:33,280 --> 00:13:34,080
Look at you.

205
00:13:35,200 --> 00:13:37,840
You're practically supporting
your whole family.

206
00:13:38,400 --> 00:13:40,000
The world's changing.

207
00:13:40,200 --> 00:13:42,560
You gotta change with it.
You gotta be tough.

208
00:13:42,960 --> 00:13:45,840
Tough? And no one's
tougher than you, Ger?

209
00:13:47,240 --> 00:13:49,360
Don't call me that.
My name's Gerald.

210
00:13:49,560 --> 00:13:50,800
Can I get you a drink?

211
00:13:51,000 --> 00:13:53,320
Give me a vodka martini.
Shake, don't stir.

212
00:13:53,520 --> 00:13:54,520
You work here?

213
00:13:54,720 --> 00:13:57,200
Weeknights, so Dorry doesn't
have to pay an extra waitress.

214
00:13:57,400 --> 00:13:58,240
That's great.

215
00:13:58,440 --> 00:14:01,640
Yeah, that's swell, if you
like working for nothing.

216
00:14:01,840 --> 00:14:04,960
Two more rounds for the pool table,
on the house.

217
00:14:06,280 --> 00:14:07,840
You haven't seen my new apartment.

218
00:14:08,040 --> 00:14:09,800
I haven't seen your old apartment.

219
00:14:10,560 --> 00:14:14,160
We're talking cable.
Can we have dinner tomorrow night?

220
00:14:15,640 --> 00:14:16,960
I'm working.

221
00:14:17,920 --> 00:14:21,200
Why don't you tell Dorry you're sick?
He can't dock your pay.

222
00:14:30,000 --> 00:14:31,440
Billy, is that you?

223
00:14:31,640 --> 00:14:33,120
Yeah, Mom. It's me.

224
00:14:33,320 --> 00:14:35,200
I'm in the kitchen.

225
00:14:37,200 --> 00:14:38,800
Merry Christmas!

226
00:14:42,240 --> 00:14:44,680
Merry Christmas, movie house!

227
00:14:45,120 --> 00:14:47,280
Merry Christmas, emporium!

228
00:14:47,760 --> 00:14:49,960
- Hi, Mom.
- Hi, sweetie.

229
00:14:50,320 --> 00:14:51,760
Do you need any help?

230
00:14:52,240 --> 00:14:54,040
Yeah, you could do the eggs.

231
00:14:54,520 --> 00:14:55,760
Thanks.

232
00:15:20,440 --> 00:15:24,320
Dad's machines work so well
the first couple of weeks, then... .

233
00:15:24,520 --> 00:15:25,960
Use the sink.

234
00:15:31,360 --> 00:15:32,960
Is something wrong?

235
00:15:33,840 --> 00:15:35,960
No, it's a sad movie.

236
00:15:39,400 --> 00:15:40,720
How was your day?

237
00:15:40,920 --> 00:15:42,160
It was fine.

238
00:15:44,800 --> 00:15:46,920
Come on, what is it?
What's wrong?

239
00:15:47,720 --> 00:15:50,760
Mrs. Deagle called again
this afternoon.

240
00:15:55,000 --> 00:15:58,000
Let's not talk about it now.
Don't say anything to Dad.

241
00:15:58,200 --> 00:15:59,400
Fine with me.

242
00:16:00,040 --> 00:16:03,080
Don we now our gay apparel

243
00:16:06,240 --> 00:16:07,840
Hi, sweetheart!

244
00:16:10,200 --> 00:16:12,480
- Welcome home.
- Hey, Dad.

245
00:16:13,840 --> 00:16:16,160
I'm glad you're back.
How was the trip?

246
00:16:16,360 --> 00:16:17,200
It was great.

247
00:16:17,440 --> 00:16:20,040
The Miracle Company, who has
the Kitchen Companion...

248
00:16:20,240 --> 00:16:23,000
...might be interested
in the Bathroom Buddy.

249
00:16:23,200 --> 00:16:24,560
Great!

250
00:16:27,440 --> 00:16:28,920
- Thanks!
- You'll like this.

251
00:16:29,760 --> 00:16:31,360
What is it? A birdcage?

252
00:16:31,920 --> 00:16:35,240
No, don't shake it. Open it now.
It won't wait till Christmas.

253
00:16:38,360 --> 00:16:39,600
It's a puppy, isn't it?

254
00:16:40,240 --> 00:16:41,360
Yeah, I can tell.

255
00:16:41,560 --> 00:16:42,960
It's a new car.

256
00:16:48,840 --> 00:16:51,400
- Honey, would you dim the lights?
- Sure.

257
00:16:51,640 --> 00:16:53,920
Dim the lights?
Does it glow in the dark?

258
00:16:54,120 --> 00:16:56,520
It's important. Trust me.

259
00:16:57,800 --> 00:16:59,360
Go ahead, open it.

260
00:17:20,760 --> 00:17:22,000
What is it?

261
00:17:22,200 --> 00:17:23,720
It's your new pet.

262
00:17:23,920 --> 00:17:25,760
Come on, Barney.
Be a good dog.

263
00:17:35,240 --> 00:17:36,960
You're kidding.

264
00:17:39,760 --> 00:17:41,560
Dad, it's really neat.

